# Realtime Patterns

Any data that multiple users can mutate **must** use Supabase Realtime — not just a one-time fetch.

## Tables requiring realtime

- `sessions` — status changes, player count
- `session_players` — players joining/leaving
- `pairings` — court assignments, match status
- `game_results` — scores recorded by any player

## Required subscription pattern

```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  // Initial fetch
  fetchData();

  // Realtime subscription
  const channel = supabase
    .channel(`session:${sessionId}:pairings`)
    .on(
      "postgres_changes",
      { event: "*", schema: "public", table: "pairings", filter: `session_id=eq.${sessionId}` },
      (payload) => {
        if (payload.eventType === "INSERT") addPairing(payload.new);
        if (payload.eventType === "UPDATE") updatePairing(payload.new);
        if (payload.eventType === "DELETE") removePairing(payload.old.id);
      }
    )
    .subscribe();

  return () => {
    supabase.removeChannel(channel);
  };
}, [sessionId]);
```

## Channel naming convention

```
session:{sessionId}:{tableName}
```

Examples: `session:abc123:pairings`, `session:abc123:players`

## Handle all three events

Always handle `INSERT`, `UPDATE`, and `DELETE` — never just INSERT.

## Debounce high-frequency updates

For the court dashboard (many events in quick succession), debounce re-renders:

```tsx
const debouncedRefetch = useMemo(
  () => debounce(() => refetch(), 200),
  [refetch]
);
```

## RLS requirement

For `UPDATE` and `DELETE` events to include old row data, tables must have:

```sql
ALTER TABLE pairings REPLICA IDENTITY FULL;
```

## Rule

- One-time `useEffect` fetch for shared data → add a Realtime subscription
- Every subscription → cleaned up in the `useEffect` return function
- Every subscription → handles INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE
